Here is the full **testsmells.org 19-smell academic catalog** audit of `UserRepositoryIntegrationTests.cs`, with integration-test calibration applied.

---

## Summary Dashboard

| Severity | Smell Count | Affected Tests |
|----------|-------------|----------------|
| High     | 3           | 3              |
| Medium   | 1           | 1              |
| Low      | 0           | 0              |
| **Total**| **4**       | **4 / 8**      |

Framework: **MSTest 4.1.0** · Integration-test calibration: **Active** (`[TestCategory("Integration")]`)

---

## Findings by Severity

### 🔴 HIGH — Sleepy Test

**File:** `UserRepositoryIntegrationTests.cs`, method `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` (line 87)

```csharp
Thread.Sleep(3000); // ← blocks for 3 seconds, non-deterministic
```

**Why it's a smell even for integration tests:** `Thread.Sleep` makes the test non-deterministic—3 seconds may be too short on a loaded CI agent, causing flaky failures; or too long, unnecessarily slowing the suite. Per Camara et al. (SAST 2021), Sleepy Tests strongly correlate with flakiness.

**Fix — poll with a timeout instead:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public async Task NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay()
{
    var user = new User("dave@example.com", "Dave");
    _repository.Insert(user);

    // Poll up to 5 s, checking every 100 ms
    var deadline = DateTime.UtcNow.AddSeconds(5);
    while (DateTime.UtcNow < deadline)
    {
        if (_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id))
            break;
        await Task.Delay(100);
    }

    Assert.IsTrue(_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id),
        "Notification was not sent within the expected window.");
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Flaky CI failures, slow feedback loops.

---

### 🔴 HIGH — Conditional Test Logic

**File:** `UserRepositoryIntegrationTests.cs`, method `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` (lines 101-108)

```csharp
if (loaded is PremiumUser premium)
{
    Assert.IsTrue(premium.DiscountRate > 0);
}
else
{
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded!.Name);
}
```

**Why it's a smell:** The test has two mutually exclusive paths—only one ever executes per run. If the production code changes the returned type, the other branch silently hides a gap. You cannot tell from test results which assertion was actually evaluated.

**Fix — split into two explicit tests:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_WhenStandard_ReturnsCorrectName()
{
    var user = new User("eve@example.com", "Eve");
    _repository.Insert(user);

    var loaded = _repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com");

    Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
    Assert.IsNotInstanceOfType(loaded, typeof(PremiumUser));
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded.Name);
}

[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_WhenPremium_HasPositiveDiscount()
{
    var user = CreatePremiumUser("eve@example.com", "Eve");
    _repository.Insert(user);

    var loaded = _repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com") as PremiumUser;

    Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
    Assert.IsTrue(loaded.DiscountRate > 0);
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Hidden testing gap—one branch is dead code you'll never notice.

---

### 🔴 HIGH — Assertion-Free Test (a.k.a. Unknown Test)

**File:** `UserRepositoryIntegrationTests.cs`, method `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` (lines 112-119)

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }
    // ← no assertion — passes as long as no exception is thrown
}
```

**Calibration note:** The name `*_RunsWithoutErrors` suggests a "does-not-throw" intent, which is *partially* valid. However, without an assertion, the test gives false confidence—data could silently fail to persist and this test would still pass.

**Fix — assert the outcome:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void BulkInsert_PersistsAllRecords()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }

    var users = _repository.ListAll();
    Assert.AreEqual(100, users.Count,
        "All 100 bulk-inserted users should be persisted.");
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** False confidence—test reports green even if `Insert` silently drops records.

---

### 🟡 MEDIUM — Assertion Roulette

**File:** `UserRepositoryIntegrationTests.cs`, method `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` (lines 35-38)

```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);          // which one failed?
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name);   // this one? 
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email); // or this?
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0);      // or this?
```

4 assertions, zero message parameters. When one fails in CI, the developer sees only a line number and must open the source to understand what property was wrong.

**Fix — add assertion messages:**
```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded, "User should be retrievable after insert.");
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name, "Name should round-trip.");
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email, "Email should round-trip.");
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0, "Id should be auto-assigned on insert.");
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Slower triage—developers waste time mapping failure line numbers to intent.

---

## Smells Checked and Found Clean (15/19)

| Smell | Status | Notes |
|-------|--------|-------|
| Mystery Guest | ✅ Clean | Uses in-memory SQLite (`Data Source=:memory:`)—no external resource dependency |
| Eager Test | ✅ Clean | No test exceeds 3 distinct production method calls |
| Magic Number Test | ✅ Clean | Count assertions (3, 10) follow immediately after adding that many items—self-documenting |
| Sensitive Equality | ✅ Clean | No `.ToString()` in assertions |
| Exception Handling | ✅ Clean | No `try`/`catch` or `throw` in test bodies |
| General Fixture | ✅ Clean | `_connection` and `_repository` are used by all 8 tests |
| Ignored/Disabled Test | ✅ Clean | No `[Ignore]` or `[TestCategory("Skip")]` markers |
| Duplicate Assert | ✅ Clean | No repeated identical assertions |
| Lazy Test | ✅ Clean | Tests exercise distinct scenarios, not redundant calls |
| Constructor Initialization | ✅ Clean | Uses `[TestInitialize]` properly |
| Default Test | ✅ Clean | Class name is descriptive and specific |
| Redundant Print | ✅ Clean | No `Console.Write*` statements |
| Redundant Assertion | ✅ Clean | No tautological assertions |
| Resource Optimism | ✅ Clean | In-memory DB, no assumed external files |
| Empty Test | ✅ Clean | All test methods contain executable statements |

The well-structured tests (`InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase`, `UpdateUser_ModifiesExistingRecord`, `DeleteUser_RemovesFromDatabase`, `ListUsers_ReturnsAllInserted`, `InsertUser_ConcurrentInserts_MaintainsIntegrity`) follow a clear Arrange/Act/Assert pattern with focused scope. These are good models to follow.

---

## Prioritized Remediation Plan

| Priority | Smell | Test | Effort | Why first |
|----------|-------|------|--------|-----------|
| 1 | Assertion-Free Test | `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` | ~2 min | **Prevents false-pass** — this test proves nothing today |
| 2 | Conditional Test Logic | `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` | ~10 min | **Eliminates hidden gap** — one branch is dead code |
| 3 | Sleepy Test | `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` | ~10 min | **Reduces flakiness** — `Thread.Sleep` is the #1 flaky-test predictor |
| 4 | Assertion Roulette | `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` | ~2 min | **Improves triage speed** — quick quality-of-life improvement |

**Bottom line:** 4 of your 8 tests have catalog smells, but the other 4 are solid. Fixing the Assertion-Free test (priority 1) is the single highest-impact change—it takes two minutes and closes a real verification gap.
